Smoking has a higher risk of losing teeth
Smoking does not only harm the lungs, but also the teeth – this is what a long-term study in Potsdam suggests.
The good news is that if you give up, the risk decreases quickly.
Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is the result of a long-term study by an international research team, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutrition Research (DIfE) in Potsdam.
Compared to non-smokers, the risk of losing their teeth prematurely was 2.5 to 3.6 times higher.
The scientists had observed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth loss are caries and inflammation of the gums, the DIfE emphasizes.
For this periodontitis, smoking is a risk factor, the authors emphasize.
The link between smoking and tooth loss is therefore due to more frequent gum inflammation in smokers.
It is not clear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of caries.
However, people who quit smoking could reduce their risk within a short period of time, the researchers write in the Journal of Dental Research.
However, it could take more than ten years for the risk to fall back to the level of non-smokers, first author Thomas Dietrich of the English University of Birmingham explained.
One must convince people to become non-smokers, study leader Heiner Boeing of DIfE explained: "Smoking shortens the lifespan."
Not smoking is good for lungs and vessels and, according to our findings, also leads to good dental health until old age.
In Germany, over 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 years is affected by toothlessness, according to the DIfE.
Previous studies have already indicated that smoking increases the risk of early tooth loss.
The new long-term study confirmed the findings.
