Jeremy Corbyn's debut at Prime Minister's Question Time
Since his election, Mr Corbyn's debut at the Prime Minister's Question Time is highly anticipated
The new Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn will make his debut at the Prime Minister's Question Time and will be playing with David Cameron for the first time.
Mr Corbyn will rise to ask the first of his six questions shortly after noon, with his performance likely to be reviewed by the media and Labour MPs.
He called for "less theatre and more facts" at this weekly event.
He also said that he could skip some sessions to leave them to colleagues.
The meeting will be the first parliamentary test for Mr Corbyn’s leadership, as it comes after his appointment as a member of the shadow cabinet and after his speech at the TUC annual meeting on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, Labour’s decision to remain silent during a 75th anniversary celebration of the Battle of Britain on Tuesday while singing the national anthem has provoked criticism from a number of Tory MPs and is at the center of several cover stories in the newspapers.
Mr Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has caught attention
A spokesman for Corbyn said he had "standing in a respectful silence" and he acknowledged the "heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of England."
But a member of Mr. Corbyn’s shadow cabinet, Owen Smith, told the BBC Two Newsnight program that he had advised the Labour chairman to sing the national anthem “independently” of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Almost a dozen shadow ministers have refused to serve on Mr Corbyn’s top team, citing differences in business, defence and foreign policy, while less than a sixth of the Parliamentary Party originally supported him as leader.
BBC Political Correspondent Robin Brant says that political differences are also “stacking” within Labour, following Mr Corbyn’s statements on the position on the European Union and the limitation of profits.
Mr Corbyn told the TUC conference that Labour is proposing changes to remove the whole idea of a limitation overall.
Hours later, Mr Smith, the shadow labor and pension minister, said the party was "very clear" that it was only against government plans to lower the limit from <0xC2><0xA3>26,000 to <0xC2><0xA3>23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labour chairman to face David Cameron over the dispatch box in Parliament in the last decade since he became Tory chief.
The Labour chairman, who promised a different policy approach, says he has "crowd-sourced" ideas for questions to Mr Cameron and has been given more than 30,000 suggestions.
The Islington North MP has said that the prime minister's questioning hour is too confrontational, and that he will refrain from both "beating readiness" and fighting with bars, and instead has set out to focus on serious issues such as poverty, inequality, and the challenges facing young people.
Mr Corbyn has said that Angela Eagle, the shadow economics minister, will represent him if he does not participate - for example, if Mr Cameron is traveling abroad.
He also brought up the idea that other colleagues occasionally take the floor and that he approached John Bercow, the speaker of the House of Commons, to discuss the issue.
When he became a leader in 2005, Mr Cameron said he wanted to move away from politics in the style of a "casper theatre," often associated with the prime minister's questioning hour, but a few years later he admitted that he had failed.
Since it was first broadcast on television in 1990, the question hour with the Prime Minister was seen as the most important barometer of a leader’s judgment and leadership in the House of Commons and his position among his parliamentary colleagues, although critics have argued that it has become a cartoon and needs far-reaching reforms.
