Pound rises due to accelerated wage growth in the UK
The pound rose sharply, according to data indicating an increase in wage growth in the United Kingdom, while the FTSE 100 was boosted by the SABMiller bid target.
Between May and July, earnings without bonuses in the UK grew 2.9% compared to the same period last year.
This percentage has been the fastest since 2009 and provided estimates of the timing of interest rate hikes.
The pound rose more than 1% against the dollar to $1,5505 and climbed to 0.84% against the euro to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1,3730.
The FTSE 100 Index closed with a 1.49% increase to 6,229.21.
SABMiller was the outstanding stock in the market and made a 20% jump following the acquisition of rival AB InBev.
A transaction would combine the two largest breweries in the world and bring together brands such as Budweiser, Stella Artois, Peroni and Grolsch.
Burberry shares were 0.9% higher after encouraging news from competitor Richemont.
Richemont’s latest sales figures beat all expectations and also showed that sales in China – a key market for Burberry – are returning to growth.
Glencore shares rose by 5% after the mining giant said it had raised $2.5 billion from a stock sale as part of its debt reduction strategy.
The stocks of the packaging and paper company Mondi were the biggest losers on the index, with a 4.3% drop after Goldman Sachs set its rating rating rating to "sell".
JD Sports rose by 3.1% after the sportswear company reported a pre-tax earnings of 46.6 million for the half-year.
JD Sports chief says higher wages are jeopardizing the expansion.
JD Sports CEO Peter Cowgill says a higher minimum wage for UK workers could mean “more purchasing power in the pockets of potential customers.”
But it is unlikely that this purchasing power will offset the higher labour costs at his company, he says.
The cost could hit JD Sports’ expansion plans, he added, and that could mean there would be fewer additional jobs.
