Metcash launches groundbreaking campaign to combat Aldi invasion
Metcash is trying to protect the IGA stores from an Aldi advance in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food Wholesaler Metcash has launched a down-to-earth campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million Aldi invasion.
While Aldi is preparing to open two distribution centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and social media marketing, as well as events such as Adelaide show.
IGA dealers and suppliers jump on board, with brands such as ice cream maker Simmo from Dunsborough distributing samples in IGA stores and store owners selling discounted tickets for the South Australian Football League to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to release further details of its defense strategy on September 29 as the wholesaler of food, alcohol and equipment conducts its annual Investor Strategy Day.
There is a lot at stake as South Australia and Western Australia account for almost 30 percent of Metcash’s IGA stores and generate higher profit margins than Metcash’s IGA network in the Eastern States.
Buyers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland – more than 30 percent in South Australia and 24 percent in Western Australia compared to around 14 percent in the Eastern States.
However, analysts like Morgan Stanley believe that twelve months after opening its first markets, Aldi will grab around five percent of the food market in these two states and take away sales from all existing stakeholders, but mainly independent retailers.
According to a report released this week, analyst Tom Kierath of Morgan Stanley estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in revenue per year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in SA and 30 in WA next year, generating revenue of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and groceries business and in quantities on Metcash’s high fixed-cost basis could cost Metcash around $13 million in profit before interest and taxes, Mr Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley estimates that Metcash’s food and grocery sales will drop by 3.8 percent in 2016, by 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, and reduce its market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, leading fund manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of Magellan Financial Group, told at a business dinner in Melbourne that Metcash is likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash refused to respond publicly to Mr. Douglass' comments.
But it is assumed that a Metcash board member contacted Mr. Douglass last week.
IGA’s market share has fallen from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and revenue from Metcash’s food and grocery trade, which supplies about 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen by 43 percent since 2012, reflecting operational debt reduction while pressure on sales and margins.
However, the wholesaler is resisting and investing more than $150 million to align sales prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products each week and improve IGA retailers in improving their stores through faster growing fresh food and delivering a better selection of private label food.
Metcash’s chief executive Ian Morrice says the price adjustments and store refurbishment programs will be on the rise, and hopes that the wholesaler will return to profit growth for the first time in four years in 2017.
Thanasi Kokkinakis is backed by President of the Australian Tennis Association Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves praise rather than criticism for his behavior.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the “collateral damages” in the recent storm around his friend Nick Kyrgios and deserves praise rather than criticism for his own behavior, according to the president of the Australian Tennis Association Steve Healy.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo, repeatedly referred to as "Special Ks", came into the limelight through Kyrgios' infamous clash with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifying game in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee, with Harrison exclaiming, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should have beaten the kid."
While last seen smashing a tennis racket after a spasm defeated a potential U.S. Open win by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was steadfastly defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place in the singles behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-finals against Great Britain.
"One thing I'm pretty excited about is the fact that, in my opinion, Thanasi was a little drawn into the dispute," Healy said.
He broke a racket when he lost in the US Open due to a spasm, but he’s not the first player to break a racket out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he’s not proud of it.
But, really, he behaved extremely well in the U.S. Open, even under the rather provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of recognition.
He has a great team around him, he has a great family around him, and I think he’s been treated a little too harshly.
He is a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard, and he fits into the team and so on, he has never had a problem with the other players, he is respected in the changing area, he trains hard, he is in good shape, he is a very stable and mature young guy, and I think he deserves to be judged by his own merits.
Healy also endorsed the decision not to include Kyrgios in the important preliminary ruling, which begins Friday, and he described the "joint decision" as the right one for everyone, but he assured the man from Canberra to return to the team as a long-term staple."
"First, we want the team to be completely focused on the competition and not on all the controversy around [Kyrgios]," Healy said.
And I think Nick made the ascent very quickly, which people like Federer and Murray have pointed out. He rises in the eyes of the public, and he has made some bad mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we try to support him, we try to make him understand the consequences of his actions. Some time outside of the spotlight where he can only think about it, I think it's the best for him, and it's the best for the team.
Europe's refugee crisis: Hungary declares emergency, closes the border, holds back refugees
Hungary declared a state of emergency and closed the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday, detaining all those who tried to enter the country illegally, all with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants.
Chaos followed at the border when hundreds of migrants accumulated in a no-man’s land and Serbian officials responded with outrage.
The people who had fled from violence were stuck for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two checkpoints of the countries and built tents and settled there.
But frustrations increased.
As a police helicopter hovered over them, the migrants chanted "Open the border!" and shouted insults to the Hungarian emergency police.
Some refused food and water in protest.
Serbia's foreign minister said it was "unacceptable" that migrants were sent back from Hungary while more and more arrived from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution and not a collateral damage.
There must be talks with Brussels and other countries in the coming days," said Ivica Dacic in Prague.
The turmoil on the Hungarian-Serbian border came a day after the 28-nation bloc was unable to agree on a common immigration policy at a disputed meeting in Brussels.
However, the ministers agreed to share the responsibility for 40,000 people who sought refuge in overwhelmed Italy and Greece, expressing their hope that eventually – next month or by the end of the year – an agreement would be reached that the EU states would take in another 120,000 refugees, including some from Hungary.
On Tuesday, Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria called for a special summit of the European Union to discuss the immigration crisis on the continent.
However, Hungary did not place its hopes on an immediate action from Brussels or its neighbors.
The emergency declared on Tuesday in two southern regions gave authorities more powers to cope with the crisis, allowing them to block roads and speed up asylum procedures.
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto, meanwhile, said that his country is also planning to build a barbed wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the influx of migrants through the country - after ending a fence at the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reported that even prisoners were used in the race to build the barbed wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a major bottleneck and entry point into the European Union for many refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East.
However, Prime Minister Viktor Orban has insisted that most arriving people are economic refugees looking for a better life, not war refugees entitled to protection – a view that is strongly inconsistent with other EU states, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, make it a crime to cross the border or damage the four-metre (13 feet) high fence that the government had erected along the southern border with Serbia, and also impose higher prison sentences for convicted traffickers.
“Due to the situation created by mass migration, the Hungarian government declares the state of emergency,” Zoltan Kovacs spokesman told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
We say it very clearly: illegal crossing is a crime.
Parliament has yet to approve the military’s deployment, which is expected next week, but Associated Press reporters have seen heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and dogs at the border for days.
Gyorgy Bakondi, state security adviser to Orban, said authorities caught 45 people trying to cross the border, 15 others had already penetrated deeper into the country.
They come over by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and are accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
The authorities are in the process of repairing the fence quickly.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a barbed-wire train wagon arrived to close the borders.
Chaos surrounded the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, when the Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process people’s data and pushed a crowd into it.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands remained outside.
Another group of migrants blocked the main motorway link between Serbia and Hungary, saying they would refuse food and water until they were allowed to enter Hungary.
2016 election: Hillary Clinton's lead to Bernie Sanders cut in half in national poll
Former U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton continues to hold a double-digit lead in the democratic race for the nomination at the national level, but Senator Bernie Sanders is gaining ground against her.
Clinton now has the support of 47 percent of Democratic voters in the primary elections (58 percent earlier), while Sanders ranks second, with 27 percent (up 17 percent).
Vice President Joe Biden, who has not yet announced whether to run for president, receives support from 15 percent of primary Democratic voters.
More than five months before the primary elections begin, most Democratic voters say it’s too early to say that their opinion is determined on which candidate they will support.
But Clinton’s supporters are more consistent in their election than those of the other candidates.
Since the CBS News poll, Clinton has lost to a number of demographic groups, while Sanders made some gains.
Clinton holds a big lead among women and moderates, but those lead have diminished.
Their support among men has fallen significantly, and Sanders is only back by 5 points.
Clinton’s advantage among democratic voters under the age of 50 has vanished, and she and Sanders are now at the same level.
However, Clinton still has a big lead among the older voters.
Last month, Clinton was ahead of Sanders with a double-digit lead to the Liberals, but Sanders now has a five-point lead to this group.
About half of the Democratic primary voters nationwide say they would enthusiastically support Clinton if nominated by the party.
A quarter would support her with some reservations and another 15 percent would only support her because she is the candidate.
Six percent would not support it.
Perhaps not surprisingly, Clinton’s current supporters are particularly enthusiastic about her.
The views are more mixed among those who do not currently support Clinton - only about a quarter would enthusiastically support her.
While 48 percent of primary Democratic voters say they enthusiastically support Clinton, fewer Republican voters say so about their top candidate Donald Trump (35 percent).
When Clinton’s supporters are asked in an open question why they want her to be the candidate, the most common answer is that she has the right experience (16%), followed by the view that it is time for a woman to become president (13%) and that she is the best candidate for the job (10%).
Clinton’s supporters also mention their connection to Bill Clinton (9 percent).
Consent to dealing with the problems and eligibility are also cited.
As the vice president throws a potential for the presidential office into the balance, 57 percent of primary democratic voters want to see him in the race - even though one third believes he shouldn't.
When Democratic primary voters are asked who would be their second choice for the party, Biden is at the forefront.
More than half of Clinton’s supporters say Biden would be their second choice far ahead of Sanders.
If Biden decides not to run for the Democratic nomination, Hillary Clinton’s lead ahead of Sanders increases from 20 points with Biden in the race to 30 points without him in the race.
Fifty-five percent of Democratic voters see Clinton as the candidate with the best chances of winning the election; however, that figure has fallen from 78 percent last month.
Biden is by far a second in this measurement, but the percentage that sees him as the “most eligible” has risen.
Nevertheless, when asked what is more important for a candidate, Democratic voters are calling questions about eligibility.
Similar to last month, no Democratic candidate or potential candidate stands out as unacceptable to these primary voters.
The Democratic candidates or potential candidates produce good results on some important characteristics among voters in their party’s primary elections.
Majorities see Clinton, Sanders, and Biden as honest and trustworthy and equipped with strong leadership skills.
Biden scores best in honesty among the three candidates, while Clinton’s strength is leadership.
Thirty percent of Democratic voters don’t believe Clinton is honest and trustworthy, twice as many say that about Sanders (15 percent), but 27 percent don’t have an opinion on him.
Democratic primary voters generally also see Clinton, Sanders, and Biden ideologically in line with their views.
In all of these measurements, about a quarter of the democratic voters do not have an opinion of Sanders.
As questions about Hillary Clinton’s use of a personal email address and a server continue to be asked during her tenure as Secretary of State, most primary Democratic voters are satisfied with their explanation of the matter, saying that it has not influenced their opinions overall.
But it’s a different story in the American public overall.
Half of Americans are now dissatisfied with their statement, while only about a third are satisfied.
Public opinion on this issue was divided in March, shortly after the problem came to light.
Most Americans said the email controversy had no effect on their general opinions of Clinton, although 36 percent said their opinions of her had worsened.
It’s mostly Republicans, more than six out of 10, who say their views of Clinton have gotten worse.
Although Clinton is considered honest and trustworthy by her party’s voters, this continues to be a problem for them among registered voters overall: only 32 percent see them as honest and trustworthy, eight percent less than last month, and 15 points less since May.
62% of voters do not consider them an honest and trustworthy person.
At the same time, 55 percent of the eligible voters across the country also see Trump as not honest and untrustworthy.
Clinton and Trump, however, get good scores in leadership.
Of the six candidates tested, Biden, Carson and Bush are the best in honesty.
A majority sees Sanders as more than honest, but as with Carson, many don’t have an opinion of him.
The error rate for the sample of 351 Democratic voters in the primary is 6 percentage points.
Ben Carson moves close to Donald Trump in nationwide poll
Ben Carson is close behind Donald Trump in the latest CBS News/New York Times poll
The two candidates now account for half of the voters’ support in the new poll, and others are dramatically losing hold.
Republican voters across the country continue to support Trump in large numbers, with support growing from 23% in the last CBS poll conducted before Fox News debate last month, by 27% in Tuesday’s poll.
But Carson shot from 6% to 23% in the same period.
The poll also found that Carson is well received by demographic groups and outperforms Trump among Republican voters with higher education.
The rest of the field, with the exception of Carly Fiorina and Ohio Governor John Kasich, has been knocked down with Wisconsin Governor Scott Walker, who fell the lowest, from 10% support last month to now 2%.
Former Florida Governor Jeb Bush, former Arkansas Governor Mike Huckabee and Florida Senator Marco Rubio are ranked third with 6%.
The margin of error in the sample of 376 people from Republican voters in this latest poll is plus or minus 6% and was conducted in September.
The latest CNN/ORC poll released last week shows Carson is rising in the polls — he ends up with 19% support among Republicans, behind Trump with 32% support.
The latest poll by ABC News/Washington Post also showed Trump clearly ahead of Carson.
Looking at a Carson rising last week, Trump found some side-slips for the former neurosurgeon, even after Carson apologized for questioning Trump’s beliefs.
“We need energy,” Trump said last Saturday during a campaign appearance in Iowa.
