Five Brotherhood Members Accused of the Death of a Baruch College Newcomer
Almost two years after a student died during a harassing ritual of a student union in Pocono Mountains, Pennsylvania, murder charges are filed against five people.
Members of the New York Baruch College Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood brutally attacked Chun "Michael" Deng during an introductory ritual in September 2013, delaying his transport to the hospital, which contributed to his death, police said.
Officials said he had been loaded with a 30-pound backpack full of sand with blindfolded eyes, and repeatedly attacked as he tried to approach a target across a frozen field.
Mr. Deng finally complained of headaches, then he fell unconscious.
The members of the Pi Delta Psi Brotherhood did not call 911 after Deng fainted and allegedly waited an hour before taking him to a hospital, police said.
However, they had time to change Deng’s clothes, google his symptoms, and contact Andy Meng, the Brotherhood’s national president, for advice, police chief Chris Wagner said at a press conference.
"At this point, the members began to hide utensils and basically put the welfare of the Brotherhood above that of Michael Deng," said police chief Wagner.
He could not be revived, and he died the next morning from his injuries.
According to an autopsy report, Deng was repeatedly injured with blunt force to the head, torso and thighs.
"Too many families have been destroyed by the bullying of the Brotherhood, and at least one student has been dying every year since 1970," Douglas Fierberg, a lawyer representing Deng's family, said in a statement.
Brotherhoods and their members must be held accountable, and this step by authorities is very important.
A Monroe County Grand Jury recommended a charge of third-degree murder for the first five members.
Thirty-two members of the Brotherhood, including Mr. Meng, are also charged with harassment and the formation of a criminal organization.
"We don't just want to blame the people involved, but if there's an organization that has - official or unofficial - sanctioned this, we will also hold it accountable," Wagner said at a press conference on Tuesday.
Baruch College has banned the Brotherhood, and the National Brotherhood has revoked its affiliation to the local group.
This will happen when the Fed raises interest rates.
An interest rate hike is coming, and the upturn will shake, yields on bonds will rise, and the economy will slip into a recession.
We know that.
What we don’t know is how long it will last and how long it will last.
In particular, history provides little guidance for the economy on how to proceed.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first interest rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The aggressiveness of the Federal Reserve in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial investments react.
That’s why U.S. central bank representatives have stressed so heavily that investors should focus not on when it begins to raise interest rates, but rather on the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants might find that the whole excitement about an interest rate hike may have been exaggerated.
“The first increase in the Fed since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the era of ‘cheap money’,” said Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, in a statement to customers.
In contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to normal highs, but still at too low levels to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there will be no impact.
Here’s a historical trend-based look at how some areas of the economy might react:
As the market has seen last month, anticipating interest rate hikes can make things volatile for a while.
Once the increase arrives, the impact is not so dramatic.
“There seems to be a tendency for asset earnings to be strangled 12 to 24 months after the first increase, which may again reflect the delay in monetary policy,” said Deutsche Bank analysts in a recent study on what happens after Fed interest rate hikes.
More specifically, the market is mostly in the upward trend over the past 35 years – about 14 percent – on the way to interest rate hikes, pretty flat in the 250 days afterwards (average gain of 2.6 percent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return of 14.4 percent in the past six past cycles, according to a recent analysis published by Bob Doll, chief investment strategist at Nuveen Management.
Deutsche Bank said that the impact on the stocks tends to occur later in the increase cycle and the return starts to decrease.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate hikes often encourage them.
In the current case, the Fed is faced with some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
It is particularly noteworthy that gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point in the Fed’s interest rate hike.
According to Deutsche Bank, for the 118 interest rate hikes since 1950, only twice the nominal GDP was below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect this to continue and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Increases in interest rates in such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky, raising the question “whether this time it’s different,” Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been anticipating a Fed interest rate hike throughout the year, and all eyes were on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting this week, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading only indicates a 25 percent probability.
“In our study, all of the increase cycles from 1950 to today took place in a super-cycle with increasing momentum in GDP and eclipsed pre-recession levels very quickly after the start of recovery,” the report said.
In contrast, this is a clearly slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
Fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an interest rate hike, and the pattern is quite similar to that of the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on stocks when they change their strategic course.
For bonds, yields seem to change direction as soon as the first increase/sink occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields fall immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
The strategists of Charles Schwab believe that the rise in interest rates will cause returns between longer and shorter bonds to come closer together and lead to flattening of the curve.
High-yield bonds often bring better returns in such a climate, although “we are still careful to expect higher returns,” said Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones believes that markets have already adapted to Fed strategy expectations.
“In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy,” she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit margins have expanded, and volatility has risen – all characteristics of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
Overall, companies that handle the greater part of their U.S. operations will benefit as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational corporations with high debt will be worse off as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market as well as financing their debt.
"History shows that 'quality' stocks tend to respond extremely positively three months after an initial interest rate hike," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for customers.
Companies with a strong balance sheet have exceeded companies with a weak balance sheet by an average of 5 percentage points after each of the rate hikes in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high capital returns and low volatility in their shares also outperformed their low-quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) respectively.
Debt becomes a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of pure stock games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savors could see profits from higher returns, even if experts disagree on how quickly this will happen.
BBC Radio 3 is a copy of Classic FM, says Member of Parliament Andrew Bingham
The Conservative Member of Parliament criticized the station for its "stupidity"
He argues that he is increasingly indistinguishable from commercial rivals.
He also targeted the BBC Music Awards and said they only imitated The Brits
Parliament's colleague Damien Collins attacked the show The Voice, saying it wasn't very original.
BBC Radio 3 is "transforming" into Classic FM, a leading member of parliament claims, increasing new pressure on the station, proving that it is doing something the private stations are not doing.
Conservative MP Andrew Bingham also told BBC bosses that the public radio station was “stupid” and increasingly indistinguishable from its commercial competitors.
"Radio 3 seems - I don't like to use the word 'stupid' - but it seems to be turning into Classic FM," he said.
He also targeted the BBC Music Awards, which launched last December.
