At their most anticipated meeting in the year, Federal Reserve strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduras mahogany table to decide if it’s time to raise the lead rate for the first time in almost a decade.
Threatening above them at one end of the decorated, two-storey meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the economic interests of the nation before all other things.
The central bank has a dual mandate from Congress: maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable here.
But since the great recession, Fed leaders have recognized that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third mandate could be the X factor in a decision that is too narrow to predict, announcing on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to be weaned from the unprecedented incentive by the near-zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
While most of the economy’s data shows solid growth, recent turbulence in global financial markets could scare already cautious Fed representatives to increase this volatility by raising interest rates on federal bonds — even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the job market and inflation will be the most important thing they are watching," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough justification to continue to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself uncertainties the financial market.
About half of the economists surveyed by Bloomberg recently predicted a rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to wait, with a key indicator indicating only a 30% chance of an increase.
This indicates a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises the rate, unless the strategists mitigate the blow by promising that a further increase is far away.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial average jumped by 228.89 points or 1.4% to 16,599.85.
The action was triggered by expectations that Fed policies will maintain the rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed would raise the rates at this point,” he said.
If she does, “she would have to go very far in her statement to calm the financial markets so they don’t panic.”
Other experts argued that a rate hike would calm the financial markets because it would eliminate uncertainty about when the Fed will trade.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen had said in spring and early summer that she expects an increase in the rate this year despite the complaints from liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed down in August, the improvement in the labour market was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed considers full employment.
Wage increases have shown signs of recovery.
And although inflation was constantly below the annual target of 2% of the central bank, the Fed representatives said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can handle higher interest rates and needs them because of the tension in the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world shrugged at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial average fell more than 16% below its peak in May, as investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would throttle global growth.
The market has recovered slightly this month, with the Dow now almost 10% below the high of May.
For the Fed representatives, the market turbulences influence the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
“If the events in the financial markets and the news about the weakness of the Chinese economy had not occurred in the last few weeks, they would have pulled the reins in this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, senior research fellow at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed employee.
Now he predicts that she will wait at least a month to better control the effects.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and there is almost no reliable data describing the developments in China," Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s main concerns, so it should not be technically involved in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the world’s monetary authority.
The influence of the central bank has been enormous in recent years.
The mere hint by then-leader Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “constrict” its monetary expansion caused confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed representatives can be expected to not only monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of Envestnet Inc’s global asset management strategy.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA, remarked this month that “the Fed has a history of overreactions to financial market movements that are apparently not linked to the economic fundamentals.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee who advocates for a rate hike, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to cut its key interest rate by 0.75 percentage points in three meetings “despite limited noticeable impact on U.S. growth,” Lacker said.
A year later, Fed representatives reversed these cuts.
The Fed should put aspects of financial stability first only during a severe crisis such as the 2008 market collapse, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s Interest Rate Settings Committee.
The recent turmoil is not coming close to this level, he said.
"She certainly doesn't want to get into the situation where she's afraid of a rate hike because the markets are upset," said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains the dual mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that is changed, I do not think it should rush ahead of time.
