Robotic cars: government wants pioneering role for Germany
According to the will of the German government, Germany should be a technological pioneer in the transformation of the car.
On Wednesday, the Federal Cabinet adopted a strategy paper from the house of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which includes investments in the expansion of digital infrastructure.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the edge of the car trade fair IAA of a "new mobility era".
Automated and connected driving will increase traffic safety and reduce congestion, Dobrindt said.
He will also discuss the issue with his counterparts from the G7 countries, who will also meet with industry representatives at the IAA.
Among other things, the Ministry of Transport’s strategy paper stresses the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a swift transition to digital radio.
To test new technology, a test track is currently being built on the Autobahn 9 in Bavaria.
In order to ensure that the driver does not face any additional liability risks, the German government intends to "examine the legal framework and, where necessary, adapt it to the new developments."
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to increase the permissible maximum speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometres per hour.
The Federal Government also wants to advocate for an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
With automated driving, the car increasingly takes the lead, the driver becomes more and more the passenger.
The technology is mainly based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study presented by the Ministry of Economics, highly automated driving on motorways will be technically possible by 2020.
Nevertheless, driverless vehicles on public roads are "only to be expected far after 2020."
The authors of the study estimate the added value in the area of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions at the location in Germany to be around 8.4 billion euros for 2025.
"The digital networking of the car can lead to more safety and efficiency in road traffic," said SPD transport politician Sören Bartol.
However, the question of liability in the event of accidents and the security of drivers’ personal data must be clearly clarified.
Yet the Germans still see self-driving cars skeptical – much more than French or Americans.
A survey conducted on Wednesday by the Forsa Institute on behalf of the audit organization Dekra found that only eight percent of Germans believe that autonomous cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32 percent expect only in 20 years, 31 percent do not believe at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomous cars by 2025, and 33 percent in the United States.
In any case, drivers in Germany are not yet ready to rely entirely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to leave control on all roads throughout the journey.
On the highway, this could be imagined in fluid traffic at least 15 percent, in traffic jams 45 percent.
One in four drivers wouldn’t let the car control them under any circumstances.
