EU wants to double mercury limit in predatory fish
The European Commission wants to double the limits for mercury in large predatory fish, thereby imposing a significantly higher dose of the nerve agent on consumers.
The consumer organization Foodwatch, which has a corresponding EU working paper, sharply criticized the plans: "The risks and side effects of failed industrial and environmental policies are passed on to pregnant women and young children with full force," explained Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limits of the nerve toxin for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as shark or swordfish, are to be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic policy reasons".
However, large predatory fish are already so heavily contaminated with mercury that, on the basis of the limits still in force, about 50 percent of the catches may not be sold.
After doubling the limit values, only 14.5 percent would be unavailable.
In return for this easing, the EU wants to tighten the limits for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
Foodwatch called this a "trick" because smaller peace fish, such as carp, are usually so low that they already meet the planned maximum levels today.
The reduction in small fish is therefore "a perfidious distraction maneuver that alone helps the economy," Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a highly toxic heavy metal for humans, which accumulates strongly over the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The German government therefore warns that "already small amounts, especially in unborn babies, can cause damage to the nervous system".
On its homepage, the Federal Ministry of the Environment declares, however, that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury is mainly released into the environment by coal combustion.
The German coal-fired power plants produce more than six tons of mercury per year, two-thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany, according to a written report from the German Federal Environment Ministry to the Greens.
The concentration of mercury in fish in Elbe, the Rhine and the Danube, for example, has been “permanently and extensively exceeded,” the “Spiegel” had quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, Europe-wide warnings about mercury in fish were already among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU warning system RASFF.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest against EU plans at: www.mercury-action.foodwatch.de
